she's saying that.

00:09:26.050 --> 00:09:26.530
TV.

00:09:26.530 --> 00:09:27.200
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:27.200 --> 00:09:28.960
JUDITH WRIGHT: She's
thinking no.

00:09:28.960 --> 00:09:30.110
So all kinds of things.

00:09:30.110 --> 00:09:31.670
It can be anything
that we overdo.

00:09:31.670 --> 00:09:32.970
So activities--

00:09:32.970 --> 00:09:34.090
they can be media.

00:09:34.090 --> 00:09:36.510
They can be engaging activities,
things that we do.

00:09:36.510 --> 00:09:39.060
So activities can become
a soft addiction.

00:09:39.060 --> 00:09:41.170
There's another category,
which is interesting.

00:09:41.170 --> 00:09:43.570
It's not doing activities,
procrastinating.

00:09:43.570 --> 00:09:45.830
How many of you are guilty
of procrastinating?

00:09:45.830 --> 00:09:47.490
And you know how we best
procrastinate?

00:09:47.490 --> 00:09:49.620
We use other soft addictions
to do that.

00:09:49.620 --> 00:09:51.060
We disappear for a
while to do this.

00:09:51.060 --> 00:09:54.810
So procrastinate, not doing the
things we wish we had done

00:09:54.810 --> 00:09:56.800
or not getting around to things,
that kind of thing.

00:09:56.800 --> 00:09:58.830
There's a third category.

00:09:58.830 --> 00:10:00.920
That's moods and
ways of being.

00:10:00.920 --> 00:10:03.450
This one was interesting to me
because you can get kind of

00:10:03.450 --> 00:10:05.230
addicted to ways of being.

00:10:05.230 --> 00:10:09.340
How many of you know really
perpetually cranky people?

00:10:09.340 --> 00:10:10.605
And it's like a habit.

00:10:10.605 --> 00:10:12.610
It's like it's a reflex.

00:10:12.610 --> 00:10:18.070
Or habitually smiley Pollyanna
types you sometimes run into.

00:10:18.070 --> 00:10:21.840
Or sarcastic, not like there
has to be wrong but there's

00:10:21.840 --> 00:10:24.360
like a reflexive, anytime
something gets uncomfortable,

00:10:24.360 --> 00:10:27.480
somebody responds with this kind
of mood or way of being.

00:10:27.480 --> 00:10:29.900
And now they're finding that
the neurochemical wash that

00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:32.960
goes on with these moods that
we get addicted to, as those

00:10:32.960 --> 00:10:36.030
moods come up, and if we're not
feeling that, we think a

00:10:36.030 --> 00:10:38.500
thought that triggers that same
neurochemical wash that

00:10:38.500 --> 00:10:39.770
brings that mood back.

00:10:39.770 --> 00:10:40.930
It's fascinating.

00:10:40.930 --> 00:10:44.680
So moods and ways of being can
be also soft addictions.

00:10:44.680 --> 00:10:46.920
And things related to activities
are just things,

00:10:46.920 --> 00:10:48.780
consumable, edible
kinds of things.

00:10:48.780 --> 00:10:51.020
And it can be your favorite
chocolate or

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:52.750
collections that you have.

00:10:52.750 --> 00:10:57.360
I was doing a talk and a woman
said, oh, I think I have a

00:10:57.360 --> 00:10:58.030
thing addiction.

00:10:58.030 --> 00:10:59.350
I said, well, most of us do.

00:10:59.350 --> 00:10:59.890
What is that?

00:10:59.890 --> 00:11:00.800
She says, well, it's a food.

00:11:00.800 --> 00:11:01.590
It's a food group.

00:11:01.590 --> 00:11:02.620
And I said, what is that?

00:11:02.620 --> 00:11:04.450
She says, it's the
eeto food group.

00:11:04.450 --> 00:11:05.490
And I was like, what is that?

00:11:05.490 --> 00:11:08.170
I thought it was like Asian
fusion or something.

00:11:08.170 --> 00:11:09.540
She said, no, Cheetos,
Frito, Doritos.

00:11:09.540 --> 00:11:10.925
I said, oh, yeah I got it.

00:11:10.925 --> 00:11:12.020
Now, I understand.

00:11:12.020 --> 00:11:14.070
So maybe that's something
of yours as well.

00:11:14.070 --> 00:11:16.500
So take just a moment or two
and take that checklist.

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:19.710
Mark anything you think you
might be susceptible to so

00:11:19.710 --> 00:11:21.230
that we're all in here
as human beings

00:11:21.230 --> 00:11:22.300
working on this together.

00:11:22.300 --> 00:11:23.360
Oh, yeah.

00:11:23.360 --> 00:11:25.890
There should be blanks on
there because anything

00:11:25.890 --> 00:11:27.790
overdone can-- even
great stuff.

00:11:27.790 --> 00:11:29.460
Playing chess can become
a soft addiction.

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:32.310
One woman told me she
volunteered too much.

00:11:32.310 --> 00:11:33.180
And she really did.

00:11:33.180 --> 00:11:35.570
She was volunteering every day
and wasn't getting on with

00:11:35.570 --> 00:11:37.540
sending her resume out, getting
a new job, things she

00:11:37.540 --> 00:11:38.220
needed to do.

00:11:38.220 --> 00:11:41.370
So even practicing an instrument
can become a soft

00:11:41.370 --> 00:11:44.460
addiction if you're over using
it to avoid some other kinds

00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:45.180
of activities.

00:11:45.180 --> 00:11:49.590
So add anything that you might
be susceptible to.

00:11:49.590 --> 00:11:50.790
Well let me find out.

00:11:50.790 --> 00:11:54.000
How many of you had more in the
activities column, more

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:55.710
stuff you over do?

00:11:55.710 --> 00:11:57.140
Let me see that.

00:11:57.140 --> 00:11:57.770
OK.

00:11:57.770 --> 00:12:00.300
How many of you more in the
avoidances, things you don't

00:12:00.300 --> 00:12:03.340
do, the procrastination or not
getting around to things?

00:12:03.340 --> 00:12:04.550
How about the mood addictions?

00:12:04.550 --> 00:12:06.610
Anybody find those for yourself,
mood or way of being

00:12:06.610 --> 00:12:07.620
addictions?

00:12:07.620 --> 00:12:09.780
How about just plain old stuff,
whether it's chocolate

00:12:09.780 --> 00:12:11.870
or collections or whatever
in that way?

00:12:11.870 --> 00:12:12.620
OK, great.

00:12:12.620 --> 00:12:15.650
The rest of you don't have soft
addictions or are you

00:12:15.650 --> 00:12:16.820
still working on it?

00:12:16.820 --> 00:12:18.370
Because I just want you to see--
and I'm not saying these

00:12:18.370 --> 00:12:19.980
necessarily are.

00:12:19.980 --> 00:12:21.640
It's our relationship
with these things.

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:23.720
And partly I really want
us to look at it.

00:12:23.720 --> 00:12:25.920
We're going to understand the
addictive nature of human

00:12:25.920 --> 00:12:30.140
beings and what to do to unlock
this so that all of the

00:12:30.140 --> 00:12:32.885
practices that we're doing are
mindful practices, our yoga

00:12:32.885 --> 00:12:35.080
that we do, our thoughtfulness,
our critical

00:12:35.080 --> 00:12:38.200
thinking, all the capacities we
have are maximized rather

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:39.520
than compromised.

00:12:39.520 --> 00:12:41.790
So that's why I want you
to be looking at that.

00:12:41.790 --> 00:12:43.140
I can tell you some of mine.

00:12:43.140 --> 00:12:44.460
And I've been working
with them.

00:12:44.460 --> 00:12:48.090
But for me it was nail
biting and catalogs.

00:12:48.090 --> 00:12:49.030
I would just disappear.

00:12:49.030 --> 00:12:51.370
I would open a catalog and it
was like I was in a dreamland

00:12:51.370 --> 00:12:54.530
for a period of time where it's
just like lots of time

00:12:54.530 --> 00:12:55.970
would go by.

00:12:55.970 --> 00:12:56.980
And I'm a reader.

00:12:56.980 --> 00:13:00.480
And a lot of times I'm reading
for stimulation, intellectual

00:13:00.480 --> 00:13:02.270
development, all kinds of
things, or research.

00:13:02.270 --> 00:13:05.310
But there's a lot of times I'm
reading it like it's just to

00:13:05.310 --> 00:13:07.350
disappear and just go mindless
for a period of time,

00:13:07.350 --> 00:13:09.490
depending on the reading
material that I have.

00:13:09.490 --> 00:13:11.540
So if I can tell you mine,
you can tell me yours.

00:13:11.540 --> 00:13:13.850
So anybody willing to share and
just shout a few things

00:13:13.850 --> 00:13:15.756
out you might have
a soft addiction?

00:13:15.756 --> 00:13:16.550
AUDIENCE: Diet soda.

00:13:16.550 --> 00:13:17.180
JUDITH WRIGHT: Diet soda.

00:13:17.180 --> 00:13:18.760
Oh, that's a really
popular one.

00:13:18.760 --> 00:13:19.050
That's great.

00:13:19.050 --> 00:13:19.920
Great, thanks.

00:13:19.920 --> 00:13:20.830
What else?

00:13:20.830 --> 00:13:21.510
AUDIENCE: Wikipedia.

00:13:21.510 --> 00:13:22.460
JUDITH WRIGHT: Wikipedia.

00:13:22.460 --> 00:13:22.850
That's great.

00:13:22.850 --> 00:13:24.100
What else?

00:13:28.860 --> 00:13:32.000
How many of you have food
addictions like chocolate or

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:33.870
salty, crunchy things
or whatever?

00:13:33.870 --> 00:13:34.260
I know.

00:13:34.260 --> 00:13:36.260
So that's a very common
one as well.

00:13:36.260 --> 00:13:38.870
So I just want you in the game
with this because if you've

00:13:38.870 --> 00:13:40.720
got one or two you're thinking
about, you're going to

00:13:40.720 --> 00:13:43.050
personalize what we're talking
about a little bit more and

00:13:43.050 --> 00:13:44.280
see what this is.

00:13:44.280 --> 00:13:47.330
This isn't about-- and we're
going to find out the wisdom

00:13:47.330 --> 00:13:48.660
that our soft addictions have.

00:13:48.660 --> 00:13:51.750
There's beautiful messages and
there's really interesting

00:13:51.750 --> 00:13:52.770
information in them.

00:13:52.770 --> 00:13:54.580
So we're going to learn to
translate those by the end of

00:13:54.580 --> 00:13:55.970
the talk today to find
out what are they

00:13:55.970 --> 00:13:56.630
trying to tell us.

00:13:56.630 --> 00:13:57.730
Why are we doing that?

00:13:57.730 --> 00:14:00.060
What's trying to get
our attention?

00:14:00.060 --> 00:14:02.450
And what's the neuroscience
underneath it that we can pay

00:14:02.450 --> 00:14:03.845
attention to it and shift it?

00:14:03.845 --> 00:14:06.950
But lest you think this is just
a phenomenon of modern

00:14:06.950 --> 00:14:08.650
times, it's not.

00:14:08.650 --> 00:14:11.880
Because many people tell
me that, oh, it's just

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:12.690
technology.

00:14:12.690 --> 00:14:13.710
That's why I'm so addicted.

00:14:13.710 --> 00:14:14.340
No.

00:14:14.340 --> 00:14:16.430
The ancient Greeks were dealing
with something very,

00:14:16.430 --> 00:14:18.210
very similar where they were
talking about that.

00:14:18.210 --> 00:14:20.650
The Greek word is akrasia.

00:14:20.650 --> 00:14:22.070
And I think it makes
you crazia.

00:14:22.070 --> 00:14:25.240
Because akrasia, it's doing
things that you know just

00:14:25.240 --> 00:14:27.440
aren't that great for you,
whether it's loss of self

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:30.750
control or over indulging in
things that aren't that great,

00:14:30.750 --> 00:14:34.880
but doing things that you don't
feel that great about or

00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:36.270
you know aren't so
positive for you.

00:14:36.270 --> 00:14:39.840
And it's interesting because
they called it acting against

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:40.930
your better judgment.

00:14:40.930 --> 00:14:43.390
How many of you ever acted
against your better judgment

00:14:43.390 --> 00:14:45.260
and then justified
it afterwards?

00:14:45.260 --> 00:14:46.740
That's part of it too.

00:14:46.740 --> 00:14:48.710
That's how you know you're in
that kind of territory.

00:14:48.710 --> 00:14:49.720
So it's really interesting.

00:14:49.720 --> 00:14:52.660
So it's fascinating because
they're the same categories,

00:14:52.660 --> 00:14:56.480
over doing activities, like I
have, and then under doing

00:14:56.480 --> 00:14:58.700
them, avoiding things, like
procrastination or putting

00:14:58.700 --> 00:14:59.740
things off, that
kind of thing.

00:14:59.740 --> 00:15:01.880
They looked at those two
categories as well.

00:15:01.880 --> 00:15:04.590
But then they're talking about
this addictive stuff.

00:15:04.590 --> 00:15:07.270
And I'm using that word for
a reason because addiction

00:15:07.270 --> 00:15:09.080
actually means in Latin--

00:15:09.080 --> 00:15:10.280
it's turning yourself over.

00:15:10.280 --> 00:15:11.710
It's giving yourself
over to something.

00:15:11.710 --> 00:15:13.710
We're not always that
considerate about what we're

00:15:13.710 --> 00:15:15.910
turning ourselves over to.

00:15:15.910 --> 00:15:19.020
And addiction means the
repetitive behaviors that

00:15:19.020 --> 00:15:21.910
we're doing and doing things
that we know aren't good for

00:15:21.910 --> 00:15:23.650
us, that are actually bad for
us, but still have the

00:15:23.650 --> 00:15:24.750
desire to do it.

00:15:24.750 --> 00:15:27.280
Who here, besides me, can admit
you've had the desire to

00:15:27.280 --> 00:15:29.640
do some things that aren't
all that great for you?

00:15:29.640 --> 00:15:31.780
And how many of you have
acted on that desire?

00:15:31.780 --> 00:15:32.950
Me as well.

00:15:32.950 --> 00:15:34.520
That's part of what
all this is about.

00:15:34.520 --> 00:15:38.170
So one of the biggest things
that gets in the way, that's

00:15:38.170 --> 00:15:43.180
related to this akrasia is we
have this fundamental issue

00:15:43.180 --> 00:15:45.490
about how we weight
consequences.

00:15:45.490 --> 00:15:48.400
Now, I think you can relate
to this because when we

00:15:48.400 --> 00:15:51.500
overweight immediate
consequences and don't think

00:15:51.500 --> 00:15:55.020
about long term-- and it's so
hard in the moment because

00:15:55.020 --> 00:15:58.310
what seems really like right
now consequences, like the

00:15:58.310 --> 00:16:01.870
comfiness of this couch, that
wonderful taste of that

00:16:01.870 --> 00:16:05.850
chocolate cake, that laughter
of that talking kitty video.

00:16:05.850 --> 00:16:07.880
You know, those things seem like
the most important thing

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:10.010
in the moment when you're
stuck by those.

00:16:10.010 --> 00:16:11.970
But other consequences
are more distant.

00:16:11.970 --> 00:16:15.670
It's like your long term career
goals or losing weight

00:16:15.670 --> 00:16:18.910
or shifting something in
your life over time.

00:16:18.910 --> 00:16:22.850
And we have this immediate
and long term.

00:16:22.850 --> 00:16:24.830
We tend to weight
the immediate--

00:16:24.830 --> 00:16:26.530
and this is evolutionary, we'll
find out in a moment.

00:16:26.530 --> 00:16:29.240
We tend to weight the immediate
much heavier than

00:16:29.240 --> 00:16:32.610
the long term, which is why we
don't often get everything we

00:16:32.610 --> 00:16:34.160
could out of life.

00:16:34.160 --> 00:16:34.845
And it's really interesting.

00:16:34.845 --> 00:16:37.580
And they call it time
inconsistency or dynamic

00:16:37.580 --> 00:16:38.306
inconsistency.

00:16:38.306 --> 00:16:39.550
But see if you can
relate to this.

00:16:39.550 --> 00:16:41.540
Here's what this study shows,
the research shows.

00:16:41.540 --> 00:16:45.420
If you're ordering food for next
week, if you're ordering

00:16:45.420 --> 00:16:48.050
some groceries for next week,
you put together a really

00:16:48.050 --> 00:16:48.990
great shopping list.

00:16:48.990 --> 00:16:51.410
It's got fruits and vegetables
and lean meats.

00:16:51.410 --> 00:16:52.160
It's really healthy.

00:16:52.160 --> 00:16:53.310
It's wonderful.

00:16:53.310 --> 00:16:57.000
However, if you go shopping
tonight, guess what you buy?

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.010
Pizza, chips, ice cream.

00:16:59.010 --> 00:16:59.740
And the studies show this.

00:16:59.740 --> 00:17:00.770
But think about it.

00:17:00.770 --> 00:17:03.310
It's a little different
now when you're

00:17:03.310 --> 00:17:05.470
streaming movies and stuff.

00:17:05.470 --> 00:17:06.480
But remember when you would
get your Netflix or other

00:17:06.480 --> 00:17:08.540
things, and you'd get things
waiting in the queue?

00:17:08.540 --> 00:17:10.980
What happens with movies, the
research shows the same thing.

00:17:10.980 --> 00:17:12.780
Like if you're thinking about
what you're going to watch a

00:17:12.780 --> 00:17:15.930
week from now, you order
really highbrow films.

00:17:15.930 --> 00:17:17.650
But if you're going to watch
something tonight, you're

00:17:17.650 --> 00:17:19.790
like, it's lowbrow stuff.

00:17:19.790 --> 00:17:20.900
It's just let me escape.

00:17:20.900 --> 00:17:23.329
Who can relate to what
I'm talking about?

00:17:23.329 --> 00:17:26.420
Or another one, like you
download books on your Nook or

00:17:26.420 --> 00:17:28.350
Kindle or your iPad or whatever
your reading device

00:17:28.350 --> 00:17:30.675
is, and you're thinking about
things you want to

00:17:30.675 --> 00:17:31.650
have there for later.

00:17:31.650 --> 00:17:35.010
And you have biographies and
histories and science text and

00:17:35.010 --> 00:17:38.840
non fiction and Nobel Prize
winning literature.

00:17:38.840 --> 00:17:41.180
And you take that and you
get it all loaded up

00:17:41.180 --> 00:17:42.140
to go on the airplane.

00:17:42.140 --> 00:17:42.900
And you're like, yes.

00:17:42.900 --> 00:17:43.410
I'm virtuous.

00:17:43.410 --> 00:17:44.220
I have all this great stuff.

00:17:44.220 --> 00:17:44.970
And you're in the airport.

00:17:44.970 --> 00:17:46.470
What do you buy to read
on the plane?

00:17:46.470 --> 00:17:47.200
AUDIENCE: "Twilight."

00:17:47.200 --> 00:17:49.500
JUDITH WRIGHT: Yeah, "Twilight."
You buy whatever

00:17:49.500 --> 00:17:51.450
you can grab to try to distract

00:17:51.450 --> 00:17:52.340
yourself in the moment.

00:17:52.340 --> 00:17:54.160
So this is what human
beings do.

00:17:54.160 --> 00:17:57.790
And it's really interesting
because we think about this.

00:17:57.790 --> 00:18:00.130
And the studies show this
over and over again.

00:18:00.130 --> 00:18:03.650
Like, the movie thing, 77% of
people order the highbrow

00:18:03.650 --> 00:18:05.880
thing now and then watch the
lowbrow thing tonight.

00:18:05.880 --> 00:18:08.270
So that means most of
us are doing this.

00:18:08.270 --> 00:18:10.600
Not that I'm not making
moral judgments.

00:18:10.600 --> 00:18:13.090
I'm just trying to wake us up
to what our habits are like.

00:18:13.090 --> 00:18:16.650
Because if you think about it,
if we really could design our

00:18:16.650 --> 00:18:19.570
lives from scratch, which
we can at a level.

00:18:19.570 --> 00:18:21.715
If we're really going to design
our lives, say, OK, how

00:18:21.715 --> 00:18:23.530
do I want my life to be?

00:18:23.530 --> 00:18:24.850
How do I want to live my days?

00:18:24.850 --> 00:18:26.600
How do I want to
spend my time?

00:18:26.600 --> 00:18:29.990
What is it that, if I could
really step back and be an

00:18:29.990 --> 00:18:32.870
architect of my own life project
and put the pieces in

00:18:32.870 --> 00:18:36.710
place and design that, I don't
think I would do this.

00:18:36.710 --> 00:18:39.320
Like, OK, got to
design my life.

00:18:39.320 --> 00:18:43.190
OK, I want to watch five
hours of TV a day.

00:18:43.190 --> 00:18:45.320
And by the time I'm 60, I want
to make sure I've spent at

00:18:45.320 --> 00:18:47.750
least nine years watching TV.

00:18:47.750 --> 00:18:49.400
And I want to have at
least 12 hours of

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:52.650
screen time every day.

00:18:52.650 --> 00:18:55.990
And that includes those
talking kitten videos.

00:18:55.990 --> 00:18:58.880
And then I want to make sure
that my kids spend more time

00:18:58.880 --> 00:19:01.450
watching TV by the time they
graduate than they've spent

00:19:01.450 --> 00:19:02.840
going to school.

00:19:02.840 --> 00:19:05.430
