00:20:59.830 --> 00:21:00.930
Yet--

00:21:00.930 --> 00:21:02.360
I know I'm exaggerating
a tiny bit.

00:21:02.360 --> 00:21:03.490
But, actually, I'm not.

00:21:03.490 --> 00:21:07.070
Because everything I just told
you is statistically normal.

00:21:07.070 --> 00:21:08.190
This is what people are doing.

00:21:08.190 --> 00:21:09.750
This is the norm in our world.

00:21:09.750 --> 00:21:11.750
We do watch five hours
of television a day.

00:21:11.750 --> 00:21:14.550
We do watch nine years of
television by the time we're

00:21:14.550 --> 00:21:15.820
60, et cetera.

00:21:15.820 --> 00:21:19.360
All those things are
statistically normal.

00:21:19.360 --> 00:21:21.790
But that's what's happening
in our world.

00:21:21.790 --> 00:21:25.720
So that means that some of us
that are listening to this are

00:21:25.720 --> 00:21:27.360
caught by some of
these things.

00:21:27.360 --> 00:21:31.290
And it's fascinating because
there's two normals, if you

00:21:31.290 --> 00:21:31.720
look at it.

00:21:31.720 --> 00:21:34.390
There's normal of what
everybody's doing, which is

00:21:34.390 --> 00:21:36.980
statistically normal.

00:21:36.980 --> 00:21:38.480
There's another normal
of the normal

00:21:38.480 --> 00:21:40.420
operating range of machinery.

00:21:40.420 --> 00:21:42.700
And that's where machines
work best.

00:21:42.700 --> 00:21:46.100
Those two normals are
very different.

00:21:46.100 --> 00:21:49.520
And they are getting farther and
farther and farther apart

00:21:49.520 --> 00:21:50.990
in our world.

00:21:50.990 --> 00:21:54.830
And because of this, because of
what's normal, if somebody

00:21:54.830 --> 00:21:59.060
doesn't think you're weird,
you're living really badly

00:21:59.060 --> 00:22:02.300
because what's statistically
normal isn't in our normal

00:22:02.300 --> 00:22:03.040
operating range.

00:22:03.040 --> 00:22:04.800
It isn't where we
function best.

00:22:04.800 --> 00:22:08.410
But that's kind of the norm of
how we are in our world.

00:22:08.410 --> 00:22:13.450
And so how many of us say,
I just want to be normal?

00:22:13.450 --> 00:22:15.940
That's not the best thing
for us at this point.

00:22:15.940 --> 00:22:19.560
And I don't want you to get smug
that this doesn't apply

00:22:19.560 --> 00:22:21.540
to you because that would be
a way of being addiction.

00:22:21.540 --> 00:22:23.640
So I'm going to check because
we're all in this.

00:22:23.640 --> 00:22:26.760
This is part of our human
nature, what's happening.

00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:28.650
So part of it, like what's
the big deal?

00:22:28.650 --> 00:22:30.020
And I think we're making
that point.

00:22:30.020 --> 00:22:32.540
And I want to just go through
some of the stats and the cost

00:22:32.540 --> 00:22:36.170
of mindlessness to really
understand how pervasive this

00:22:36.170 --> 00:22:39.170
is and how that no matter how
much mindful work we do, how

00:22:39.170 --> 00:22:42.220
this subtracts from that and
keeps us from having the juice

00:22:42.220 --> 00:22:43.570
that every day could have.

00:22:43.570 --> 00:22:47.360
So all these kind of mindless
activities that we so

00:22:47.360 --> 00:22:51.920
naturally gravitate to, they
mute our consciousness.

00:22:51.920 --> 00:22:53.490
They numb our feeling.

00:22:53.490 --> 00:22:55.710
So they reduce our emotional
intelligence.

00:22:55.710 --> 00:22:58.960
They reduce our social emotional
intelligence, which

00:22:58.960 --> 00:23:01.760
affects our decision making
and our intimacy and our

00:23:01.760 --> 00:23:04.490
genuineness and our contact with
ourselves and our ability

00:23:04.490 --> 00:23:07.110
to really relate and
be creative.

00:23:07.110 --> 00:23:08.420
It steals time.

00:23:08.420 --> 00:23:11.240
Tremendous amounts of time are
eaten up in things that we're

00:23:11.240 --> 00:23:13.640
not that aware of.

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:16.210
Oh, the intimacy, it diminishes
intimacy because

00:23:16.210 --> 00:23:17.420
we're not there.

00:23:17.420 --> 00:23:19.880
We're not fully present
with ourselves and

00:23:19.880 --> 00:23:20.920
another human being.

00:23:20.920 --> 00:23:23.610
And there was a recent study
at the University of Essex,

00:23:23.610 --> 00:23:24.730
this was fascinating.

00:23:24.730 --> 00:23:26.670
If you're out with someone and
you're trying to have a more

00:23:26.670 --> 00:23:28.530
meaningful conversation, you're
sitting across the

00:23:28.530 --> 00:23:31.840
table or next to someone, if
there's even a cell phone on a

00:23:31.840 --> 00:23:34.650
table near you-- no one's
even talking on it.

00:23:34.650 --> 00:23:37.990
Just having that cell phone on
the table as you're talking

00:23:37.990 --> 00:23:39.850
reduces intimacy.

00:23:39.850 --> 00:23:43.560
It lowers the trust and the
sense of connection and the

00:23:43.560 --> 00:23:45.490
depth of the conversation.

00:23:45.490 --> 00:23:48.190
And they think it's because
it's an indication that

00:23:48.190 --> 00:23:49.460
there's other people.

00:23:49.460 --> 00:23:51.280
It kind of represents there's
other people and you're not

00:23:51.280 --> 00:23:54.390
just with the person, or it
could interrupt you in any

00:23:54.390 --> 00:23:57.210
second so you don't relax
into the engagement.

00:23:57.210 --> 00:23:58.120
But that in itself--

00:23:58.120 --> 00:24:01.260
so the clues are there that are
disrupting intimacy, much

00:24:01.260 --> 00:24:02.900
less when we're actually
on that when we're

00:24:02.900 --> 00:24:04.470
at dinner with someone.

00:24:04.470 --> 00:24:05.470
Multitasking.

00:24:05.470 --> 00:24:08.450
And there's no such thing as
multitasking, even though most

00:24:08.450 --> 00:24:09.760
of still try it.

00:24:09.760 --> 00:24:12.200
We only pay attention to
one thing at a time.

00:24:12.200 --> 00:24:14.500
And we're flipping back and
forth between things.

00:24:14.500 --> 00:24:16.860
We're not as good at things
as we think we are.

00:24:16.860 --> 00:24:19.800
But what happens when we
multitask or really

00:24:19.800 --> 00:24:23.320
compulsively check our email--
the norm is 36 times an hour,

00:24:23.320 --> 00:24:23.800
by the way.

00:24:23.800 --> 00:24:25.890
That's statistically normal.

00:24:25.890 --> 00:24:32.080
So what happens then is that
we lower our IQ 10 points,

00:24:32.080 --> 00:24:34.030
which is the same as
smoking a joint.

00:24:34.030 --> 00:24:36.350
I'm not recommending one or the
other necessarily, but to

00:24:36.350 --> 00:24:39.270
kind of get what happens going
on in our noggin when

00:24:39.270 --> 00:24:40.570
this is going on.

00:24:40.570 --> 00:24:44.970
So what I say is it makes us
numb and dumber and fat and

00:24:44.970 --> 00:24:47.280
fatter and all the other
implications that it has.

00:24:47.280 --> 00:24:48.920
And it's a huge issue for us.

00:24:48.920 --> 00:24:51.350
And it also costs
a lot of money.

00:24:51.350 --> 00:24:54.360
Because if you think about it,
just think about it-- just a

00:24:54.360 --> 00:24:59.850
handful of songs on iTunes and
a book or so on your reading

00:24:59.850 --> 00:25:03.000
device or gourmet coffee,
you start to add

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:03.990
things up over time.

00:25:03.990 --> 00:25:05.070
It really adds up.

00:25:05.070 --> 00:25:07.000
And I've done these trainings
now with thousands of people

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:08.560
over the last 20 years.

00:25:08.560 --> 00:25:10.390
The lowest amount we ever
heard people-- they do a

00:25:10.390 --> 00:25:12.320
financial accounting to kind
of get the point for

00:25:12.320 --> 00:25:12.730
themselves.

00:25:12.730 --> 00:25:14.410
Oh my gosh, it's so sobering.

00:25:14.410 --> 00:25:16.460
The lowest I've ever
seen anybody was

00:25:16.460 --> 00:25:18.240
$3,000 for the year.

00:25:18.240 --> 00:25:19.670
And this person was pretty
much a hermit.

00:25:19.670 --> 00:25:23.340
He actually had avoidance
soft addiction.

00:25:23.340 --> 00:25:26.430
The norm was $30,000
a year of just

00:25:26.430 --> 00:25:27.910
kind of mindless spending.

00:25:27.910 --> 00:25:30.280
And if you want to spend that,
that's totally fine.

00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:32.490
But usually it's just money that
goes somewhere they were

00:25:32.490 --> 00:25:35.320
not aware of, that's not going
towards what it is that we

00:25:35.320 --> 00:25:36.370
really want.

00:25:36.370 --> 00:25:38.610
So part of the deal with
this-- let me kind of

00:25:38.610 --> 00:25:39.750
personalize this a bit.

00:25:39.750 --> 00:25:41.490
And then we're going to play
with the neuroscience under it

00:25:41.490 --> 00:25:43.360
and find out why this is.

00:25:43.360 --> 00:25:48.565
Part of why I've studied human
potential for all these years

00:25:48.565 --> 00:25:51.710
is because there was something
that I was looking at it in my

00:25:51.710 --> 00:25:53.880
own life that I felt like there
was something more there

00:25:53.880 --> 00:25:55.190
that I wasn't quite getting.

00:25:55.190 --> 00:25:56.940
And I thought I was
living life well.

00:25:56.940 --> 00:25:58.390
But something was
missing for me.

00:25:58.390 --> 00:26:01.010
See if you can relate to some
of things I'm talking about.

00:26:01.010 --> 00:26:02.820
I don't think your story
should be mine.

00:26:02.820 --> 00:26:05.860
But just see what you can
see because I knew about

00:26:05.860 --> 00:26:06.570
achievement.

00:26:06.570 --> 00:26:09.100
I was always a great student.

00:26:09.100 --> 00:26:10.870
I was valedictorian
of my class and

00:26:10.870 --> 00:26:11.900
graduated summa cum laude.

00:26:11.900 --> 00:26:14.090
And I was able to achieve.

00:26:14.090 --> 00:26:15.400
And I was able to--

00:26:15.400 --> 00:26:18.570
I rose to national prominence
in two different careers by

00:26:18.570 --> 00:26:19.850
the time I was 28.

00:26:19.850 --> 00:26:22.060
So I knew how to do well.

00:26:22.060 --> 00:26:25.580
But at the same time I was
having career success, I was

00:26:25.580 --> 00:26:28.590
overweight, overwrought,
overstressed.

00:26:28.590 --> 00:26:29.740
There was--

00:26:29.740 --> 00:26:32.160
even despite my success,
I was really unhappy.

00:26:32.160 --> 00:26:33.780
I felt very empty.

00:26:33.780 --> 00:26:35.820
And I felt like I was
sleepwalking through my life.

00:26:35.820 --> 00:26:37.330
I was doing a lot of things,
but there was a

00:26:37.330 --> 00:26:38.460
numbness that I had.

00:26:38.460 --> 00:26:40.080
Something like life was
out there but I

00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:41.940
wasn't touching it.

00:26:41.940 --> 00:26:43.000
How many of you know what
I'm talking about?

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:44.690
That numb kind of sleepwalking
feeling?

00:26:44.690 --> 00:26:47.930
How many of you are too numb
right now to raise your hand?

00:26:47.930 --> 00:26:52.950
And I couldn't seem to
break what that was.

00:26:52.950 --> 00:26:54.300
And I tried a lot of things.

00:26:54.300 --> 00:26:55.500
So I lost weight.

00:26:55.500 --> 00:26:56.970
I got a guy.

00:26:56.970 --> 00:27:00.140
I worked harder.

00:27:00.140 --> 00:27:01.620
I meditated more.

00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:03.060
I prayed.

00:27:03.060 --> 00:27:04.310
And it kind of helped.

00:27:04.310 --> 00:27:05.560
But it didn't really
unlock it.

00:27:05.560 --> 00:27:07.030
And then I partied a lot.

00:27:07.030 --> 00:27:07.690
Where are my partiers?

00:27:07.690 --> 00:27:08.950
I got to make sure we've
got a few of us.

00:27:08.950 --> 00:27:09.840
They usually sit in the back.

00:27:09.840 --> 00:27:10.740
So, hey, good.

00:27:10.740 --> 00:27:11.520
There's a few of us.

00:27:11.520 --> 00:27:14.450
So whatever it was, I kept
trying to try new things to

00:27:14.450 --> 00:27:16.740
try to unlock this pattern.

00:27:16.740 --> 00:27:18.590
And it wasn't working.

00:27:18.590 --> 00:27:21.240
And I was just getting so
frustrated with my life

00:27:21.240 --> 00:27:23.250
because I thought it
was a formula.

00:27:23.250 --> 00:27:26.600
You do well, you try hard, you
have success, whatever.

00:27:26.600 --> 00:27:27.930
It didn't work.

00:27:27.930 --> 00:27:31.440
But what happened was that I
realized through some of the

00:27:31.440 --> 00:27:32.270
work I was doing--

00:27:32.270 --> 00:27:35.940
I started a demonstration
program, one of the first

00:27:35.940 --> 00:27:40.000
programs in the country to set
up programs for students with

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:42.140
disabilities to be successful
on campus.

00:27:42.140 --> 00:27:44.160
And I designed it and did
research and designed this

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:45.170
model program.

00:27:45.170 --> 00:27:47.660
So I had these students--

00:27:47.660 --> 00:27:50.280
paraplegic, they were
quadriplegic, or blind or deaf

00:27:50.280 --> 00:27:51.820
or cerebral palsy, all
kinds of things they

00:27:51.820 --> 00:27:53.320
were dealing with.

00:27:53.320 --> 00:27:57.280
And then I also had a program
after that that I started at a

00:27:57.280 --> 00:27:59.870
university for little children
that had developmental

00:27:59.870 --> 00:28:02.290
disabilities and
their families.

00:28:02.290 --> 00:28:04.830
And there was something that I
noticed because these people

00:28:04.830 --> 00:28:07.090
were dealing with some
really tough stuff.

00:28:07.090 --> 00:28:10.350
It wasn't easy to be doing
what they were doing.

00:28:10.350 --> 00:28:14.710
And I realized that many of
these students and many of

00:28:14.710 --> 00:28:17.770
these families with these tough
situations they were

00:28:17.770 --> 00:28:22.560
dealing with were much
happier than I was.

00:28:22.560 --> 00:28:25.520
And the contrast was
very stark for me.

00:28:25.520 --> 00:28:28.280
And it was upsetting to me.

00:28:28.280 --> 00:28:30.120
I was happy that they
were happy.

00:28:30.120 --> 00:28:32.470
But I couldn't understand
what was going on.

00:28:32.470 --> 00:28:35.265
And I discovered something
at that point.

00:28:35.265 --> 00:28:37.500
And I had kind of an epiphany.

00:28:37.500 --> 00:28:39.510
It didn't happen
in one moment.

00:28:39.510 --> 00:28:43.360
But it kind of dawned on me
that there was something

00:28:43.360 --> 00:28:45.160
really wrong with the formula
that I was going

00:28:45.160 --> 00:28:46.260
about my life with.

00:28:46.260 --> 00:28:50.880
Because I thought it was being
good, being a good girl, and

00:28:50.880 --> 00:28:55.360
working hard and being perfect
and doing well at work and

00:28:55.360 --> 00:28:57.590
having a perfect body, perfect
situation, perfect

00:28:57.590 --> 00:28:59.080
circumstances.

00:28:59.080 --> 00:29:02.890
And that wasn't it.

00:29:02.890 --> 00:29:06.080
And it was very upsetting
to me to realize.

00:29:06.080 --> 00:29:07.920
Because the people I was working
with didn't have

00:29:07.920 --> 00:29:11.400
perfect circumstances or bodies
or minds or whatever,

00:29:11.400 --> 00:29:14.080
yet there was a quality of
life that I didn't have.

00:29:14.080 --> 00:29:17.130
And it really woke me up because
I realized, wait a

00:29:17.130 --> 00:29:20.160
minute, it's not the formula
that I thought it was.

00:29:20.160 --> 00:29:23.550
Because I work hard and then
try to have some recovery.

00:29:23.550 --> 00:29:25.540
I would work hard and
then meditate.

00:29:25.540 --> 00:29:26.750
I work hard, recovery.

00:29:26.750 --> 00:29:28.040
Who's my work hard, recovery?

00:29:28.040 --> 00:29:28.810
How may of you know that one?

00:29:28.810 --> 00:29:29.900
You work hard and
then collapse,

00:29:29.900 --> 00:29:31.270
work hard and collapse.

00:29:31.270 --> 00:29:34.140
That formula wasn't
doing it for me.

00:29:34.140 --> 00:29:37.335
And I finally woke up and I
realized that-- and it was

00:29:37.335 --> 00:29:39.930
very upsetting to me because
it was so disturbing--

00:29:39.930 --> 00:29:41.210
that it really wasn't
about that.

00:29:41.210 --> 00:29:42.680
It was about consciousness.

00:29:42.680 --> 00:29:45.730
It was about being mindful, not
