00:32:03.820 --> 00:32:05.520
And I want to talk
about this more.

00:32:05.520 --> 00:32:07.780
That's why I came up with the
term soft addiction because I

00:32:07.780 --> 00:32:10.650
was also working with a lot of
high achieving people who

00:32:10.650 --> 00:32:13.780
weren't making the progress in
all the quality of their life

00:32:13.780 --> 00:32:15.230
that they really needed
or wanted.

00:32:15.230 --> 00:32:17.480
And that this was the
same kind of thing

00:32:17.480 --> 00:32:18.950
that I found in them.

00:32:18.950 --> 00:32:21.050
So why is it this way?

00:32:21.050 --> 00:32:22.810
Why is it so easy to fall?

00:32:22.810 --> 00:32:25.310
And why are the statistical
norms the way they are?

00:32:25.310 --> 00:32:28.310
Why is it so easy to fall into
all these habits and things

00:32:28.310 --> 00:32:30.970
that we do that deprive us of
the quality of life and

00:32:30.970 --> 00:32:34.670
connection and sense and
presence and consciousness?

00:32:34.670 --> 00:32:36.070
But there is an answer to it.

00:32:36.070 --> 00:32:38.270
And it's important for us to
understand it because it's

00:32:38.270 --> 00:32:39.550
evolutionary.

00:32:39.550 --> 00:32:42.910
Because what happens is
evolution should have weeded

00:32:42.910 --> 00:32:45.480
all this stuff out if it
wasn't good for us.

00:32:45.480 --> 00:32:50.320
But it can't because what
happens-- do you love this?

00:32:50.320 --> 00:32:51.690
It's a little parody.

00:32:51.690 --> 00:32:58.310
But what happens in evolution is
our circuits that we have,

00:32:58.310 --> 00:33:00.750
we're always scanning for
threats or scanning for

00:33:00.750 --> 00:33:01.570
opportunities.

00:33:01.570 --> 00:33:04.640
That's what kept us alive
with early man.

00:33:04.640 --> 00:33:06.110
Is there a saber-toothed
tiger coming?

00:33:06.110 --> 00:33:07.240
Where's their food?

00:33:07.240 --> 00:33:11.650
Those circuits that are always
scanning are what our survival

00:33:11.650 --> 00:33:13.210
is based on.

00:33:13.210 --> 00:33:17.490
But our soft addictions co-opt
those very circuits that we

00:33:17.490 --> 00:33:19.330
can't get rid of because
they're part

00:33:19.330 --> 00:33:20.740
of our being alive.

00:33:20.740 --> 00:33:21.550
So co-ops those.

00:33:21.550 --> 00:33:25.840
So it hijacks these systems
we have in our brain that

00:33:25.840 --> 00:33:29.900
condition us to look for
food, for sex, to keep

00:33:29.900 --> 00:33:30.780
us away from predators.

00:33:30.780 --> 00:33:33.610
It's those same systems
that it takes.

00:33:33.610 --> 00:33:37.720
So what happens is that we start
seeing threats as highly

00:33:37.720 --> 00:33:44.250
salient and things that might
be novel or give us a little

00:33:44.250 --> 00:33:48.480
dopamine burst as something
that's really salient for us.

00:33:48.480 --> 00:33:51.220
So everything gets translated
into either food, sex,

00:33:51.220 --> 00:33:53.480
circuits, or threats.

00:33:53.480 --> 00:33:56.400
So what happens, we start
seeing-- and we're really

00:33:56.400 --> 00:33:58.010
wired for the salience.

00:33:58.010 --> 00:34:03.394
So what happens, we start seeing
salience in chocolate,

00:34:03.394 --> 00:34:08.679
in, oh, let's see, yeah, for TV,
wet t-shirt contests start

00:34:08.679 --> 00:34:12.420
looking really interesting to
us because it captures that

00:34:12.420 --> 00:34:16.000
same circuit that's kept us
alive and kept us procreating

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:17.340
throughout life.

00:34:17.340 --> 00:34:20.620
So part of why this is so
important for us to understand

00:34:20.620 --> 00:34:23.239
is that we're hardwired to pay
attention to things that we

00:34:23.239 --> 00:34:24.139
think are salient.

00:34:24.139 --> 00:34:27.239
But we start seeing those
immediate consequences as

00:34:27.239 --> 00:34:30.540
being more salient to us than
something long term.

00:34:30.540 --> 00:34:35.570
So same thing, if we were like
an ancient man or woman and

00:34:35.570 --> 00:34:40.850
there's a lion, we're going to
immediately deal with that and

00:34:40.850 --> 00:34:42.790
stop building our hut.

00:34:42.790 --> 00:34:45.250
So the longer term thing
gets pushed aside.

00:34:45.250 --> 00:34:46.810
And that's pretty much
how we're wired.

00:34:46.810 --> 00:34:48.800
And we need to be
aware of that.

00:34:48.800 --> 00:34:51.570
So what happens is that soft
addictions capitalize on this

00:34:51.570 --> 00:34:53.699
ready-made programming for us.

00:34:53.699 --> 00:34:57.810
Now, what we need to do-- so the
longer term evolution of

00:34:57.810 --> 00:35:01.790
us and our older brain and
our limbic system is

00:35:01.790 --> 00:35:03.260
wired for the survival.

00:35:03.260 --> 00:35:05.090
That's what gets captured
all the time.

00:35:05.090 --> 00:35:07.480
And I'm going to teach you
about those neuroscience

00:35:07.480 --> 00:35:10.470
circuits and those
in just a second.

00:35:10.470 --> 00:35:12.750
But what need to do is use our
frontal lobe or prefrontal

00:35:12.750 --> 00:35:15.180
cortex, which is the more
recently evolved part of our

00:35:15.180 --> 00:35:17.160
brain, which is the more highly
developed part of our

00:35:17.160 --> 00:35:19.660
brain that can counteract
that.

00:35:19.660 --> 00:35:21.600
That's a part of our brain
that's interested in the long

00:35:21.600 --> 00:35:24.690
term, in our dreams, in our
yearnings and possibilities

00:35:24.690 --> 00:35:27.060
and what can happen and who can
we become and what can the

00:35:27.060 --> 00:35:29.850
world be and what we can
invent and discover.

00:35:29.850 --> 00:35:32.560
And all the things that create
all the beautiful things you

00:35:32.560 --> 00:35:36.690
create here are from this part
of our brain as it overrides

00:35:36.690 --> 00:35:39.260
some of those more
early signals.

00:35:39.260 --> 00:35:40.200
And it's really important.

00:35:40.200 --> 00:35:41.780
They've done some-- you may
have heard of the famous

00:35:41.780 --> 00:35:43.420
marshmallow study.

00:35:43.420 --> 00:35:45.520
So Walter Mischel did this
study-- some little

00:35:45.520 --> 00:35:46.650
four-year-olds.

00:35:46.650 --> 00:35:48.860
And they had this choice.

00:35:48.860 --> 00:35:50.650
They sat at these little tables
and they had this

00:35:50.650 --> 00:35:51.260
little marshmallow.

00:35:51.260 --> 00:35:53.850
And they said, look, you can eat
the marshmallow right now.

00:35:53.850 --> 00:35:56.610
But if you can wait a little
bit, you can have two

00:35:56.610 --> 00:35:57.940
marshmallows.

00:35:57.940 --> 00:36:00.590
Well, these four-year-olds,
it was so--

00:36:00.590 --> 00:36:01.910
there's videos all
over of them.

00:36:01.910 --> 00:36:02.660
You can watch them.

00:36:02.660 --> 00:36:04.140
They're going crazy
with these.

00:36:04.140 --> 00:36:05.840
They want to eat the
marshmallows so badly.

00:36:05.840 --> 00:36:07.020
They're like licking it.

00:36:07.020 --> 00:36:08.880
They're grabbing the middle of
it and trying to pretend they

00:36:08.880 --> 00:36:10.400
didn't eat it.

00:36:10.400 --> 00:36:12.730
And a lot of the kids just gulp
it, just gulp the one

00:36:12.730 --> 00:36:13.210
marshmallow.

00:36:13.210 --> 00:36:16.470
And other kids found
delaying tactics.

00:36:16.470 --> 00:36:17.100
They sing.

00:36:17.100 --> 00:36:18.320
They sit on their hands.

00:36:18.320 --> 00:36:20.240
They spin around on
their chairs.

00:36:20.240 --> 00:36:21.020
They look away.

00:36:21.020 --> 00:36:23.840
They distract themselves and
wait and got the second

00:36:23.840 --> 00:36:25.130
marshmallow.

00:36:25.130 --> 00:36:27.730
This is a really important
experience for you to

00:36:27.730 --> 00:36:31.220
understand because those
children that waited for the

00:36:31.220 --> 00:36:34.600
two marshmallows, they studied
them longitudinally.

00:36:34.600 --> 00:36:38.320
And by the time they were
adolescents and even later,

00:36:38.320 --> 00:36:42.030
their social development was
way beyond the other kids.

00:36:42.030 --> 00:36:46.340
Also their SAT scores were 210
points on average higher.

00:36:46.340 --> 00:36:50.090
So that being able to delay
gratification, to look at what

00:36:50.090 --> 00:36:52.980
a bigger reward later
is really critical.

00:36:52.980 --> 00:36:54.450
It's a really important thing.

00:36:54.450 --> 00:36:56.060
And that's part of what
we need to be able

00:36:56.060 --> 00:36:57.610
to be looking at.

00:36:57.610 --> 00:37:01.470
But what happens, if we're
easily distracted by the buzz

00:37:01.470 --> 00:37:05.820
in our pocket or a chime of an
email or a smell of coffee or

00:37:05.820 --> 00:37:06.730
whatever it is--

00:37:06.730 --> 00:37:08.150
we're easily distracted.

00:37:08.150 --> 00:37:11.030
All of sudden we forgot about
the two marshmallows of life

00:37:11.030 --> 00:37:14.070
and we've gobbled the one and
we've not gotten the two.

00:37:14.070 --> 00:37:15.880
So there's much better
gains for us if we

00:37:15.880 --> 00:37:17.560
can sort this through.

00:37:17.560 --> 00:37:22.010
So what happens with this
addictive process is anything

00:37:22.010 --> 00:37:26.360
that triggers the possibility
of reward sends this amazing

00:37:26.360 --> 00:37:29.850
dopamine squirt into
your brain.

00:37:29.850 --> 00:37:31.320
And I'm going to have you play
