00:37:31.320 --> 00:37:33.940
I'm going to tell you a little
bit how this works.

00:37:33.940 --> 00:37:37.050
And there's two different--

00:37:37.050 --> 00:37:38.760
I'm going to skip ahead
a little bit, Kate.

00:37:38.760 --> 00:37:44.220
There's two different circuits
in our brain that really help

00:37:44.220 --> 00:37:48.410
us orient either to this
immediate pleasure or this

00:37:48.410 --> 00:37:50.270
longer term kind of goal.

00:37:50.270 --> 00:37:51.935
And I'm going to make this
distinction so I want you to

00:37:51.935 --> 00:37:52.530
have the difference.

00:37:52.530 --> 00:37:56.870
Because what happens, this
addictive process happens--

00:37:56.870 --> 00:37:59.720
we have these hedonic
hot spots.

00:37:59.720 --> 00:38:03.050
And actually what happens is
that there's one center in our

00:38:03.050 --> 00:38:06.210
brain that wants and craves.

00:38:06.210 --> 00:38:09.200
And there's another center
of our brain that yearns.

00:38:09.200 --> 00:38:10.630
And it's different.

00:38:10.630 --> 00:38:12.590
I'm going to have you have an
experience of this and then

00:38:12.590 --> 00:38:14.750
I'm going to unpack this
a little bit for you.

00:38:14.750 --> 00:38:16.660
So what happens is that we--

00:38:16.660 --> 00:38:18.210
many of the neuroscientists
have found this.

00:38:18.210 --> 00:38:20.320
We have things that we want.

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:22.470
But the wanting is very

00:38:22.470 --> 00:38:24.040
different than liking something.

00:38:24.040 --> 00:38:26.320
These two centers-- sometimes
they call it the wanting

00:38:26.320 --> 00:38:30.430
center or the center of
excitement in our brain or the

00:38:30.430 --> 00:38:31.790
seeking center.

00:38:31.790 --> 00:38:34.080
And it's the one that gets
fueled by dopamine.

00:38:34.080 --> 00:38:36.920
And it's really intrigued by
the possibility of reward.

00:38:36.920 --> 00:38:38.660
But it's not the
reward itself.

00:38:38.660 --> 00:38:40.430
And this is when we get
a little bit crazed.

00:38:40.430 --> 00:38:43.170
We're kind of ah, ah,
ah and oh, oh, oh.

00:38:43.170 --> 00:38:45.480
You get that little buzzed
kind of look.

00:38:45.480 --> 00:38:49.660
On the other hand, we are
not wired for being

00:38:49.660 --> 00:38:52.460
sated in that center.

00:38:52.460 --> 00:38:55.760
There's another center
for being satisfied.

00:38:55.760 --> 00:38:58.410
And they're different neural
circuits that do this.

00:38:58.410 --> 00:39:00.610
The dopamine center
is our wanting.

00:39:00.610 --> 00:39:02.730
It's what gets us kind of
motivated and high and gets us

00:39:02.730 --> 00:39:04.200
to start engaging.

00:39:04.200 --> 00:39:07.340
And the other center is
fueled by opioids.

