00:50:32.050 --> 00:50:32.710
reduce stress.

00:50:32.710 --> 00:50:34.470
But it's not all the mindless
stuff we do.

00:50:34.470 --> 00:50:35.520
It's talking with a friend.

00:50:35.520 --> 00:50:36.850
It's listening to music.

00:50:36.850 --> 00:50:38.650
It's reading something
beautiful.

00:50:38.650 --> 00:50:40.610
It's exercising.

00:50:40.610 --> 00:50:41.620
It's being in nature.

00:50:41.620 --> 00:50:44.470
It's all the things that
actually reduce our stress and

00:50:44.470 --> 00:50:46.640
bring our brain functions
back.

00:50:46.640 --> 00:50:48.470
So any other questions
or thoughts

00:50:48.470 --> 00:50:48.880
that you want to share?

00:50:48.880 --> 00:50:49.550
Yeah?

00:50:49.550 --> 00:50:50.762
AUDIENCE: I'd like to know
a bit more about

00:50:50.762 --> 00:50:52.240
the avoidance ones.

00:50:52.240 --> 00:50:54.440
JUDITH WRIGHT: Yeah.

00:50:54.440 --> 00:50:57.300
Yeah, if you look at it,
avoidances have meaning.

00:50:57.300 --> 00:50:58.860
There's a yearning behind
those as well.

00:50:58.860 --> 00:51:03.030
Oftentimes, procrastination,
there's a yearning for

00:51:03.030 --> 00:51:06.160
comfort, a yearning for
security, a yearning for

00:51:06.160 --> 00:51:08.390
protection.

00:51:08.390 --> 00:51:10.730
One of the reasons people
procrastinate is that they

00:51:10.730 --> 00:51:12.710
know the minute they start
working on something they're

00:51:12.710 --> 00:51:15.420
going to get driven so they
limit the amount of time that

00:51:15.420 --> 00:51:16.270
they're going to work on it.

00:51:16.270 --> 00:51:17.020
That's not everybody.

00:51:17.020 --> 00:51:18.170
But some people do that.

00:51:18.170 --> 00:51:21.100
So they're trying to protect
themselves from getting lost

00:51:21.100 --> 00:51:21.710
in some way.

00:51:21.710 --> 00:51:23.790
So for each person the yearning

00:51:23.790 --> 00:51:24.890
can be a little different.

00:51:24.890 --> 00:51:26.130
But there is a different
yearning.

00:51:26.130 --> 00:51:27.990
How many of you are
procrastinators?

00:51:27.990 --> 00:51:29.750
I have been one and am one.

00:51:29.750 --> 00:51:31.880
And it's really interesting
because it's hard to see

00:51:31.880 --> 00:51:35.310
what's the positive, what's the
yearning underneath that.

00:51:35.310 --> 00:51:37.910
But often time it's a way that
we're trying to take care of

00:51:37.910 --> 00:51:42.420
ourselves rather than adding
things to our life

00:51:42.420 --> 00:51:43.870
that would calm us.

00:51:43.870 --> 00:51:47.270
Because procrastination,
we're usually scared.

00:51:47.270 --> 00:51:49.090
We may not have the information
we need.

00:51:49.090 --> 00:51:50.650
We may need more help.

00:51:50.650 --> 00:51:54.140
It may feel like a big cliff
we've got to get over.

00:51:54.140 --> 00:51:55.770
And we need more help.

00:51:55.770 --> 00:51:56.820
We need more resources.

00:51:56.820 --> 00:51:58.330
We need more strategy.

00:51:58.330 --> 00:52:00.520
And it's a clue for us to
prepare and take care of

00:52:00.520 --> 00:52:02.730
ourselves rather than
just a push it away.

00:52:02.730 --> 00:52:04.770
Does that work for you?

00:52:04.770 --> 00:52:05.590
Thank you.

00:52:05.590 --> 00:52:07.330
Yeah.

00:52:07.330 --> 00:52:08.580
OK, great.

00:52:13.656 --> 00:52:15.863
AUDIENCE: I was wondering, what
was it about the people

00:52:15.863 --> 00:52:18.089
you learned from, the people who
you were taking care of--

00:52:18.089 --> 00:52:19.043
disabled--

00:52:19.043 --> 00:52:22.382
that enabled them
to avoid these?

00:52:22.382 --> 00:52:24.770
Did they not have the time?

00:52:24.770 --> 00:52:27.580
JUDITH WRIGHT: You know, it's
interesting because I'm not

00:52:27.580 --> 00:52:30.510
sure exactly how to describe
what their

00:52:30.510 --> 00:52:31.650
motivation was or whatever.

00:52:31.650 --> 00:52:35.890
But there was something about
they were so present in the

00:52:35.890 --> 00:52:38.100
moment doing what they could
to learn and grow and take

00:52:38.100 --> 00:52:40.450
advantage of the situations
that they had,

00:52:40.450 --> 00:52:42.260
that it wasn't about--

00:52:42.260 --> 00:52:44.300
they couldn't be under the
illusion that someday

00:52:44.300 --> 00:52:45.730
it'll all be OK.

00:52:45.730 --> 00:52:48.180
Someday it'll all be perfect.

00:52:48.180 --> 00:52:49.210
So they weren't so--

00:52:49.210 --> 00:52:52.130
there was a being present
and a genuineness.

00:52:52.130 --> 00:52:55.210
They couldn't hide
their mistakes.

00:52:55.210 --> 00:52:57.630
Like one guy I worked with,
he was deaf and he

00:52:57.630 --> 00:52:58.820
had cerebral palsy.

00:52:58.820 --> 00:53:01.510
And he came to me one day
and he was laughing.

00:53:01.510 --> 00:53:02.600
I said, what are you
laughing about?

00:53:02.600 --> 00:53:04.270
And he said, I was just at
the-- he used sign there.

00:53:04.270 --> 00:53:06.410
I was just in the cafeteria
and I was eating my lunch.

00:53:06.410 --> 00:53:07.370
You know, I've got CP.

00:53:07.370 --> 00:53:09.040
So the food's flying
all over the place.

00:53:09.040 --> 00:53:09.860
And it's all over me.

00:53:09.860 --> 00:53:11.220
And I said, what's so
funny about that?

00:53:11.220 --> 00:53:12.660
And he said, all the
kids were laughing.

00:53:12.660 --> 00:53:14.030
And I said, what's so
funny about that?

00:53:14.030 --> 00:53:17.650
And he said, I can't
hear them.

00:53:17.650 --> 00:53:20.100
So wow, there was just this--

00:53:20.100 --> 00:53:21.860
I'm not saying that everybody
was like that.

00:53:21.860 --> 00:53:25.090
But there was this just dealing
with what life had in

00:53:25.090 --> 00:53:29.430
the moment, vulnerably, present
with feelings, with

00:53:29.430 --> 00:53:32.710
the upset, the frustration,
the anger, the joy of any

00:53:32.710 --> 00:53:35.455
small success that
was an experience

00:53:35.455 --> 00:53:37.790
that I wasn't having.

00:53:37.790 --> 00:53:39.840
And the families that were
dealing with these little kids

00:53:39.840 --> 00:53:41.700
with these disabilities, the
ones that went through the

00:53:41.700 --> 00:53:44.480
tough work of mourning the loss
of the child they thought

00:53:44.480 --> 00:53:46.765
they were going to have so they
could love the one they

00:53:46.765 --> 00:53:50.150
had, there was an appreciation
and acceptance of what was,

00:53:50.150 --> 00:53:53.220
what is, that created a lot
more satisfaction and

00:53:53.220 --> 00:53:55.800
happiness in those families
even after the so-called

00:53:55.800 --> 00:53:57.890
tragedy and then before.

00:53:57.890 --> 00:54:00.910
So there's this facing a reality
and being genuine in

00:54:00.910 --> 00:54:03.670
the moment that was a quality
that I hadn't been having in

00:54:03.670 --> 00:54:04.220
my own life.

